On 3/20/25, at 13:24 hours, an FRA inspector in the CSXT Acca Yard discovered UTLX 630359, a loaded tank car of sodium hydroxide solution, had leaked from manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, Associated Asphalt Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC (report# 2025-0320-00129). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found release was caused one of six manway cover bolts being less than tool tight.  Contractor personnel tightened the manway cover bolts and decontaminated the exterior of the car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- David Taylor (804-704-7242).

column169: MULX 701436 arrived on MOED-10 on R2, loaded car of propane was found to be leaking B end liquid line.  At approximately 2300 hrs, 3/10/2025, Hepaco received a call from Rita Mager, Berkshire & Eastern RR, requesting a response to leaking tank car at the Deerfield Yard.  Hepaco arrived on site at 0100 hrs, 3/11/2025, and held safety briefing.  At 0115 hrs, track protection was received and Hepaco mounted car.  It was found that the B end liquid valve was not secured and the liquid valve secondary closure plug was less than tool tight.  Hepaco made corrections in form of securing both the liquid valve and secondary closure.  0230 hrs, Hepaco offsite.  There was no waste generated from this incident.
column170: Shippers to ensure liquid lines and vapor valves are properly tightened and adequately prepared for transportation to avoid leakage.

At the end of the offload our driver hooked up an airline that runs from the compressor on the tractor to an air inlet valve that comes off of the discharge valve used for sampling and blowing the lines clean at the end of offloading.  He turned on the air compressor and opened the external valve partially and began walking the line but it wasn't get light like it should.  he looked back and saw that the end of the airline connected to the compressor on his truck came off the connection and product was backflowing from his product hose into the discharge valve and ultimately through the airline and on to the ground.  Estimating 16 ounces hit the ground.
column170: He felt that the grommet / gasket made a solid connection and looked good when he first hooked it up.  After he replaced the grommet the connection remained strong and he was able to finish clearing his lines out appropriately.  We are bringing him in for follow up training to ensure he knows how to recognize when a gasket is going bad and should be replaced.

On 3/21/25 @0130ct while unloading the trailer the warehouseman removed a pallet of drums and as he exited the trailer he heard a thud. When he looked back into the trailer he noticed that a 55 gallon drum from the pallet behind the one he had just removed had vallen over due to the pallet board breaking allowing the drum to tip over. The lid on the drum burst open allowing all the contents of the drum to be released into the trailer floor. The material ran to the back and out of the trailer into the containment in front of the dock. The release was contained to the trailer floor and the containment well at the dock. There was no contamination of soil or a water way. They immediately put down absorbent and called for a response team to assist with the clean up. The team showed up at 1300 and began to clean up the area with absorbents and placed them into the appropriate containers for disposal. They then pumped out the containment well @1430ct and did a final wipe down with absorbents. They were compete @1600ct.
column170: The combination of an inadequate pallet an the failure to shrink wrap the drums together on the pallet for securement created the situation for the drum to tip over. The team responsible for the pick up and loading of the containers were informed of the requirements of securing the containers and were given retraining on load securement to complete.

column169: On 3/4/2025, our forklift operator was moving totes out of the way to load trailers. He took a tote to the lower yard to make room on the dock. He misjudged how close he was to another tote and that the forks stuck out beyond the width of the tote. This resulted in the tote behind being punctured with a 4X2" hole.  The forklift operator got help from a coworker right away, they were able to flip the tote on its side on a spill pallet. Once the tote was on the spill pallet, dock employees notified their supervisor. The forklift operator placed booms and spill pads to keep the material contained. A drum vac was used to vacuum up standing liquid from the ground.  The supervisor immediately notified upper management about the spill. The supervisor was given a list of numbers to contact, one of those being Environmental Restitution to dispatch an emergency response (ER) team to respond to perform clean-up. Until the ER team arrived on-site, employees made sure everyone kept out of the area and that the spill was contained.  Once the ER team got to work, they transferred the waste into a new tote. This included material from the spill pallet, drum vac drum, and the remaining material in the punctured tote. The ER team decontaminated everything, pH tests were taken and about 10 yards of soil was dug up and placed into a roll-off bin. We are waiting for sample results in order to dispose of the soil.
column170: We are considering the possibility of moving to a larger location so we have more room to work and to reduce handling of waste. We are looking into getting shorter forks for our forklifts.

It was reported that due to improper loading, approximately .5 gallon of NQ Solve 1110 (hazardous - UN2059) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and they felt comfortable cleaning the release donning the proper PPE per SDS. The released product, 2 damaged lids, and oil-dri will be placed into a 55-gallon metal drum.  The 2 lids of the damaged drums will be replaced and sealed to move on to the Consignee. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. There is no regulatory reporting required for this release. ERTS will upload the BOL, SDS and create a waste container entry. ERTS contacted Alex (Chemtrec) who provided report #2025032600102.

ERTS will upload the BOL, SDS and create a waste container entry. ERTS contacted Larry (Infotrac) who provided report #384-445.

AT RC-1 SINGULATOR, BELT TENDER NOTICED HAZMAT PACKAGE HAD A WET SPOT ALL OVER HALF OF THE BOTTOM PORTION. BELT TENDER NOTIFIED RMP THROUGH THE RADIO ABOUT THE HAZMAT PACKAGE AND RMP NOTIFIED DESIGNATED RESPONDER. DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED AT RC-1 SINGULATOR WITH THEIR SPILL CART, FULL PPE ON, AND CURRENT DECISION TREE. DESIGNATED RESPONDER READ AND FOLLOWED THE CURRENT DECISION TREE, WHICH LEAD TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET SINCE THERE WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL. SINCE THERE WAS NO PUDDLE UNDERNEATH PACKAGE, NO ZEP ZORBENT WAS NEEDED. DESIGNATED RESPONDER CONTAINED FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAZMAT PACKAGE AND RETURNS BACK TO THE PSC CAGE. DESIGNATED RESPONDER STARTED PROCESSING THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAZMAT PACKAGE. AFTER PUTTING THE SOLIDIFIED CONTENTS AND CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD IN GREEN BAGS, DESIGNATED RESPONDER DECONTAMINATED THEIR PPE USED FROM THE RESPONSE.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

Shipment under AWB 020-16746601 was accepted for transportation as general cargo. Cargo was transported on flight LH455/05MAR SFO-FRA which is the passenger flight. Further cargo was transported on truck from FRA to DRS. Upon cargo arrived at Lufthansa cargo facility in Dresden it was noticed that 1pc of 2 damaged. One damaged fiberboard box on top of pallet. Leaking liquid causes acidic damage at forklift and warehouse floor. No declaration of dangerous goods at package and docs. After requesting a safety data sheet it turns out to be UN1805 phosphoric acid. No injuries. Other packages on pallet under damaged box are contaminated. The entire shipment was stopped at DRS until further notice.   There is more hidden DG UN1824 included in the shipment (see attached MSDS/docs). These docs were provided by the agent. This DG (UN) was not part of the damaged piece. No spillage or other irregularities was detected for this hazardous material except that it was undeclared.  The MSDS for the leaking DG was attached on the outside of the damaged piece (see one of the pictures). So, access/knowledge about the contents was readily available.
column170: Shipper must understand the basic principles of transportation hazardous material by air. Shipper staff must be trained.

At 1730 ET, XPO-XLA notified ERTS of a cargo release. It was reported that approximately 4-5oz of Clethodim 2e released from a plastic tote due to improper loading (strap rubbed on the tote causing a release). The release impacted the concrete dock and inside trailer#317-8081. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4 to 5 ounces of UN1993 Clethodim 2e product released from the plastic tote due to a strap rubbing on the corner. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into (2) 200-gallon poly/UV totes due to the excess product. The old tote was triple rinsed and is now considered RCRA empty. Contractors placed impacted PPE in (1) 55-gallon metal drum and impacted oil dry in another (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding several leaking plastic jugs containing hazardous product, Isopropyl Alcohol 70%. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 21-gallon release of product onto cardboard and the wooden trailer floor in a 4’x4’ area as a result of improper loading. The contractor containerized 84-bottles of product into one 55-gallon DM for waste disposal. Another 55-gallon DM was generated for waste disposal containing impacted cardboard and debris. XPO will manage all of the waste generated from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

Driver was loaded for store in Springville, UT. While on I-15 southbound lane the Driver struck a piece of road debris that was a metal rod at MM 275. Driver was in middle lane and could not avoid the object. When the object was struck it was thrown into his passenger side fuel tank on the truck creating a hole in this fuel tank. Driver pulled over to check the equipment and realized the fuel tank was leaking. Solar dispatched Environmental Restoration LLC to begin clean up. The diesel tank on the truck was full roughly 100 gallons released on the side of the I-15. Estimated 30 gallons impacted a drain along I-15 the other gallons stayed on concrete and was able to be collected via absorbent material. Environmental Restoration dispatched a Vac truck and Jet Rodder to clean the lines of the drain system. This clean up generated three 55-gallon drums of absorbent and impacted debris as well as the contents of the Vac truck.
column170: No further training was given as we feel it was unavoidable road debris.

Driver of vehicle owned by Pilot Travel Centers crossed an uncontrolled rail-grade crossing without performing the necessary steps to ensure the crossing was clear. As a result, a train made contact with the trailer, resulting in a release of 1400 gallons of diesel fuel from the trailer. Additionally, a fuel tank on the train engine was ruptured, resulting in a release of 600 gallons of dyed diesel.
column170: All drivers for Pilot Travel Centers LLC will be retrained in the proper procedures when approaching and crossing rail grade crossings. Training will include: stopping between 15-50 feet from crossing, looking and listening for approaching train(to include radio off and windows down), ensuring there is enough space to cross without stopping and never stopping on the tracks. Emergency message will be sent to all drivers on 3/17/25 and formal training with drivers will begin on 4/1 and conclude on 6/30

SET Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, they observed an estimated (1) gallon of material released from one (1) 330-gallon plastic tote that was cracked at the top of the tote from improper preparation for shipping. SET Environmental personnel observed that the released material impacted 3 ft-by-2 ft of trailer and concrete dock floor. SET Environmental personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and containerized them along with the cut-up tote and PPE into two (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The remaining material in the product tote was to be transferred to two (2) 275-gallon IBC tote. Generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the Dayton Freight Lines team to coordinate disposal.

column169: On 03/19/2025 at approximately 1300 hours, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 393838 at the ramp facility in Fort Worth, reporting a presumed gasoline spill.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box that contained about 4 glass bottles of liquid.  The shipment was discovered where liquid had completely absorbed into the outer packaging and emitted a gasoline odor.  Further investigation revealed one broken bottle and a saturated safety data sheet "crude oil" inside of the box for; however, the odor from the shipment indicates otherwise.  The shipment displayed an Excepted Quantities mark, but the amount of liquid in each inner contents appears to exceed the limits shown in IATA Regulations.  The shipment is being held. pending an FAA investigation.

column169: First Call Environmental-LTL personnel arrived onsite and observed that an estimated five (5) gallons were released impacting an estimated 2’-by-2’ area. The released material was due to a load shift causing one (1) 5-gallon metal pail to be punctured. Once the telehandler arrived, they started unloading freight. They ceased work due to being unable to unload/reload a metal grate with product on it with the manpower and equipment they had. However, the driver called his safety manager who dispatched two drivers who had power pallet jackets to assist with moving the metal grate. If loaded in the original position, the freight risked puncturing another product. It was determined the metal grate should be taken on another truck instead of being reloaded in the same position. First Call Environmental-LTL deployed absorbents and containerized them into two (2) 55-gallon metal drums. All undamaged freight was loaded onto a new truck while the metal grate was loaded onto the original truck. Due to First Call Environmental-LTL not being able to hold hazardous waste, they took the generated waste the ESTES terminal in West Middlesex, Pennsylvania. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.
Freight was stacked on top of other freight.

column169: While the Aircraft loading agents were unloading the cargo bin of our CRJ 200, and as the checked bag was going down the belt loader, the bag caught fire. Seeing flames and smoke, the fire was reported to local emergency responders. The bag was extinguished using a fire extinguisher before the responders could arrive on scene.  The crew and passengers were unaware if the incident occurred in flight or taxing to the gate. The duration of the event was only a few minutes until the items were extinguished. The aircraft cargo bin did not appear to have any damage and no smoke alarms inside the aircraft were reported. The aircraft was grounded until further inspections was made.  Upon closer inspection of the bag, there was a small hole that had burned through the bag. Two of the personal electric battery powered items inside the bag were charred. An undetermined brand of cell phone and a Remington beard trimmer. It is undetermined which item caused this event. The national response center was notified shortly after the event.
column170: Although the passenger was not in violation of any current regulation as the battery was contained inside equipment, all passengers are informed via signage on the dangers of placing items containing batteries in checked luggage.

column169: On March 6, 202, at 0900 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Day & Ross personnel in Winnipeg, Manitoba regarding the release of Sodium Bisulfite Solution. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 10.5 gallons of Sodium Bisulfite Solution (UN2693, 8, III) from (1) 275-gallon poly tote onto the concrete dock. The release was due to a screw protruding from the bottom of the pallet that punctured the tote underneath, impacting a 10’ x 10’ area of the concrete dock. No drains or waterways were found to be impacted by the release. The release was cleaned with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DFs which were staged onsite, along with the damaged tote, by contractors for proper disposal.

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that there were seven trooper vehicles, 4 fire trucks, and CEMA personnel onsite assisting with cleanup, too. The released material impacted the trailer floor and the asphalt of the highway. Clean Harbors personnel transferred an estimated two hundred and twenty-five (225) gallons of material to a new tote using an onsite gravity transfer. The damaged and new totes were offloaded from the trailer. The contractor estimated fifty (50) gallons of Ethanol was released from the tote. There were no areas to clean in the trailer because the Ethanol had evaporated. A hazmat driver from Clean Harbors arrived to assist with taking the trailer, both totes, and waste to the West Sacramento ESTES terminal. The empty tote and the tote of product were labeled and staged in the center of the dock near 136 door. The waste generated will remain onsite for the ESTES team to coordinate disposal. It is recommended the asphalt at the site of the release should be pressure washed.

column169: On 3/12/2025, at 12:29 hours, FRA Inspector David Robinson, reported at the CSX Moncrief Yard in Jacksonville, Florida the GATX 205634, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquid, N.O.S (Turpentine) was leaking from the vapor line valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, International Paper Co, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2025031200135). Hulls Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve partially open and secondary closure plug less than tool tight. Contractor personnel closed the vapor line valve and properly tool tighten the secondary closure plug. Contractor personnel also corrected 1 of 6 manway swing bolts less than tool tight that was identified by the FRA inspector.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Marceia Cox (901-229-4591).

column169: On 03/26/2025, at 12:57 hours, FRA Inspector Quinton Grant reported PROX 280006, a loaded tank car containing acetone, was leaking from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Advansix, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2025-03-26-00144). Marion Environmental Inc (MEI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line leaking between the base of the liquid line valve and tank car’s pressure plate. MEI personnel were able to tighten the liquid line valve mounting bolts and stop the release.   Contractor personnel verified the car built 6 psi of pressure in the tank car and remained leak free. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Jeffery Matlack (804-530-6285). The tank car was delivered to Whitaker Industries with the approval from FRA Inspector Kevin Cash.

column169: On 03/08/2025, at 1313 hours, personnel at the CSX yard in Selkirk, New York, reported product leaking from inside the valve box of car IAPX 1084, a tank car residue: last contained, Argon, refrigerated liquid.  The car was isolated and the customer, Airgas, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2025-03-08-00044). David Scoons, a CSX Senior Manager of Hazardous Materials, responded to the incident along with HEPACO a CSX emergency response contractor. It was determined the cause of the release was due to the liquid line valve being partially and the secondary securement not properly applied.  Response personnel closed the valve properly secured the valve and secondary securement stopping the release.  The shipper’s representative, George Ryan (518-526-3322), was notified of the condition found and the corrective actions taken.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 275-gallon tote containing hazardous product, Scale Trol-G. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 1-gallon release onto the top of the tote and onto the wooden trailer floor in a 4’ x 4’ area as a result of improper packaging – a faulty cap on the tote. The contractor replaced the cap on the tote and performed a slosh test. The tote passed and was shipped on to the consignee. The release was cleaned up with Kolor Safe neutralizer and absorbent rags. One 30-gallon DF of waste was generated containing the neutralized, impacted rags. XPO will manage all waste generated from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: At 21:30 EST on 3/3, XPO-XGR contacted ERTS to report a spill of about 2 gallons of "1.4 Low VOC Cleaner" from 4x 1-gallon metal pails on the dock floor. The box was punctured by a forklift at XGR. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined the terminal did not have sufficient PPE to clean the spill, citing goggles. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of UN1263 1.4 Low VOC Cleaner product released impacting 2’x4’ area of the dock floor due to forklift puncture. The crew restacked the pallet and wiped down the other products which had been impacted by the spill. There was (1) 1-gallon bottle found damaged and the other 3 in the punctured box were not damaged. The waste was collected into (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The  waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

B-Ann Driver was dispatched for a power unit only load for Southwest Logistics/ OFS Inc. B-Ann Driver picked up trailer #463 in OKC and picked up a load of Ferric Chloride in Russelville Arkansas and Delivered to Topeka, KS. The driver noticed a tire separating on the trailer, he contacted Southwest Logistics/OFS Inc dispatch for direction on where to go for repairs. Southwest Logistics dispatcher sent B-Ann Driver to Loves truck stop El Dorado KS. Upon arrival B-Ann Driver noticed a leak on the trailer. He contacted Southwest Logistics Dispatcher, who contacted Don Cox. OFS INC/ Southwest Logistics Safety Manager, Don Cox then contacted Boomer Enviriomental to contain and Clean up spill

He contacted Southwest Logistics Dispatcher, who contacted Don Cox. OFS INC/ Southwest Logistics Safety Manager, Don Cox then contacted Boomer Enviriomental to contain and Clean up spill

At 14:50 EST ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (LHO) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading, an unknown amount of NPS Sodium Persulfate (hazardous - UN1505) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor at dock door #9. The caller has requested a contractor out for cleanup and containment and to bring drums for containment (Jeff Smith - Service Center Mgr approved). There is no regulatory reporting required for this release. ERTS will upload the BOL, SDS and create a waste container entry. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed less than a pound of the UN1505 Sodium Persulfate product released to a 1’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor and impacting the shrink wrap due to improper loading. The crew overpacked the fiber drums (2) 55-gallon poly drums and placed the PPE into a 30-gallon poly drum and submerged the PPE in water prior. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box, containing a metal can.  Transport Canada flagged this shipment and selected it for further inspection, which revealed that the shipment was not declared properly as dangerous goods.  Transport Canada acquired the commercial invoice, which identified the commodity as Iodopropane.  The shipment traveled without required markings, labeling, packaging, or paperwork in accordance with IATA Regulations.  At the request of Transport Canada, the shipment will be destroyed.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: Global Crossing Airlines, Inc {GCXA} operates freighter services under an ACMI agreement with IBC Airways to Kingston, Jamaica and several cities inside Cuba. As of 02/15/2025, GCXA's Loadmasters; who accompany the aircraft as part of the crew, have detected several instances where Lithium Batteries were found as being undeclared in shipments prior to loading the aircraft. Since 02/15/2025, instructions from the Cargo Operations department of GCXA has been for the Loadmasters to remain vigilant and scrutinize all shipments that may be viewed as suspicious, i.e {labeling, marking on boxes, key words such as "generators" "batteries" etc) prior to loading any ULD's onboard the aircraft. On 03/13/2025, the Loadmasters working the flight scheduled for MIA-CFG-MIA, indicated at 07:08L that again {6th time since 02/15/25), Undeclared hazardous materials were found in the shipment prior to loading and consequently rejected the entire load. The instructions to the ground handler {NAS) was for them to break all the packages since the Loadmasters did not trust any items that were wrapped with black plastic shrink wrap. The Loadmasters reached out for guidance to the Cargo Operations leadership and was advised to stand firm on that decision to reject this shipment. The Loadasters instructed the ground handlers to begin inspecting the completed ULDs and eventually various items ranging from portable electric generators, undeclared car batteries to electric scooters were detected. IBC Airways were informed and eventually they cancelled the flight.  The FAA CMT was informed of the events.
column170: Since this has been an ongoing situation, GCXA's Cargo Operations department has been attempting to support IBC Airways in mitigating these events. Several attempts were made since 02/15/2025 to notify, educate and discuss to the IBC Airways leadership and staff the importance of compliance and mitigating the issues that were identified and rejected.  The root causes identified were gaps in the acceptance process and IBC Airways as the freight fowarder/consolidator were not advising their clients of the requirements or putting the necessary actions in place.  02/15/2025- GXA3909 MIA-CMW: Undeclared Lithium ION batteries- Location IBC Airways warehouse/ramp 02/19/2025- GXA3909 MIA-HAV: Undeclared Lithium ION batteries- Location NAS warehouse/ramp 03/01/2025- GXA3909 MIA-CMW: Undeclared Lithium ION batteries/mislabel- Location IBC Airways warehouse/ramp 03/07/2025- GXA3913 MIA-HAV: Undeclared Lithium ION batteries- Location IBC Airways warehouse/ramp 03/10/2025- GXA2966 MIA-HAV: Undeclared Lithium ION batteries- Location IBC Airways warehouse/ramp 03/13/2025- GXA3933 MIA-CFG: Undeclared Lithium ION batteries- Location NAS warehouse/ramp 03/13/2025- GXA3911 MIA-SNU : Undeclared Lithium ION batteries- Location NAS warehouse/ramp  All Undeclared Hazardous materials were rejected by the Loadmasters and 4 flights liste¿ above had to be cancelled.

column169: Facility personnel reported a leak from IM tank RMCU10056.  Upon investigation by a contractor it was determined the leak was the result of the Manway Gasket not properly installed which allowed product to leak out when lifted from chassis prior to loading into railroad well car.

Vehicle left the road and overturned, damaging cargo tank on ledge. Product flowed out of tank until 3rd party cleanup contractor, Clean Harbors, arrived approximately 3 hours later. Clean Harbors evacuated the remained of the product and recovered any recoverable spilled oil. Removed contaminated soil and installed monitoring wells on site, which will be monitored for 1 year.   5/7/2025 - Damage was more than $500. However, we do not have a total number for damage yet because repairs and remediation are still taking place.

At 02:08 EST on 3/7, Tony Hobson with XPO-LJS contacted ERTS to report a spill of about 2 quarts of an unidentified material onto the trailer floor from a pallet of boxes. The pallet was poorly loaded and damaged in transit from XDM. The material cannot be identified as the pallet is wrapped in opaque shrink wrap, and ERTS advised the terminal not to handle the material as it is a regulated corrosive. ERTS will dispatch a contractor to assist. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of UN2491 Hood & Flue Cleaner Concentrate product released to a 2’x3’ area of the trailer floor and small amount to the concrete floor due to a forklift puncture. The crew found (2) boxes damaged, each containing (4) ½ gallon jugs each. The crew cleaned up the spill with citric acid. The cardboard, damaged poly jugs, waste product, oil-dri, citric acid and PPE were containerized into (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Our driver was dropping NA1993 ULSD into our underground storage tank. The tank 90% flapper lid closed and stopped the flow of product. Our driver thought the rest of the product in the drop hose could fit, so the driver unlatched the drop fitting to let air in and the product to continue flowing into the tank. The flapper lid remained closed and the product spilled approximately 15 gallons onto our parking lot. Our driver used our trailer spill kit along with the store spill kit to contain the spill and clean up the area. No product reached any drains or soil. The product was disposed of into our hazardous waste bins.
column170: Our terminal leadership investigated this incident into why this spill occurred. It was determined to be driver error. We are taking steps to mitigate the process that was used above and to ensure that the practice does not continue to be used. We have procedures that are to be followed in the instance the incident occurs again.

column169: At 2009 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XSD. It was reported that approximately 1 gallon of "Sodium Hypochlorite" was released from a plastic drum due to improper loading. The release impacted the inside of trailer #3171103. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed  approximately 15-gallons of UN1791 Sodium Hypochlorite product released impacting wooden trailer floor, concrete and asphalt. The release appears to have been caused by forklift damage which occurred when the pallet the freight was loaded on broke resulting in the drum dropping down into the pallet. The crew utilized absorbents, simple green and water on the impacted areas. The (4) 5-gallon drums were overpacked into an 85-gallon poly drum, impacted absorbents, PPE and impacted plywood were containerized into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column44: BONDERITE C-AK ZX-1 ALKALINE CLEANER (PARCO CLEANER ZX-1)
column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a punctured tote containing hazardous product, BONDERITE C-AK ZX-1 ALKALINE CLEANER. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 200-gallon release onto the concrete dock floor and parking lot in a 100’x70’ area as a result of a forklift puncture. Oil dry was applied to the released material and a tote transfer was performed for the residual product left inside of the damaged tote. In total, 23 drums of waste were generated from this response that were taken by the contractor and staged at their location for waste management. The customer refused the new tote with the transferred product, so XPO staged the tote in the waste area for waste disposal. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: On 3/31/2025, at 10:22 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parsons Yard discovered tank car NATX 301995, residue: last contained Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S., leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Berryman Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2025 0331 000056).  EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaving from the bottom outlet valve. Contractor personnel determined the release was the result of a faulty bottom outlet valve and a secondary closure that was less than tool tight.  The car was fully empties of its contents and the secondary closure cap secured.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Sarah Lombardo (832-571-2514).  The car was held at location pending further repair by a certified MRU or receipt of a OTMA from FRA.

column163: ER COORDINATOR ON BEHALF OF HIGHWAY TRANSPORTATION
column169: Driver observed material leaking down the side of his tanker. Driver inspected the top of the tanker and observed there was no dome lid gasket. Driver reported to his Safety Department, and they called Environmental Management, Inc. (EMI) to initiate a response. EMI contacted a local subcontractor, Haz Mat Special Services (HMSS), to respond to the release. HMSS arrived and placed absorbents underneath the tanker. HMSS cleaned around the dome lid and crash box and then installed a new gasket and secured the dome lid. The side of the tanker was then wiped down with absorbent pads. A power Washer was used to wash the side of the tanker and all the reinstate was captured. The tanker was then moved forward and the absorbents swept up and, placed into a 55-gallon open-top drum. The area on the concrete parking lot, which was approximately 10 feet in diameter, was then power washed and the water collected. All waste was placed into the one (1) drum and removed from the site for disposal at a later date.
column170: Shipper should have informed driver that no gasket was in place.

column169: Univar Solutions' driver was delivering Sulfuric acid to our customer in West Groton, MA. Customer advised driver on arrival that the load would not fit as it was ordered too early. Driver and customer planned to stop the delivery at 3600 gallons on customer's tank meter (relative to Storage tank capacity of 4000 gallons). During unload, driver went to check the meter at 3300 gallons and found the tank overflowing into the containment dike. The overflow was coming from the overflow pipe. It did not come out of the top of the tank at any time. Delivery was immediately stopped. Customer was notified of the spill as she was not aware it happened. Customer's Supervisor was alerted to the spill by the receiver.  Customer supervisor advised their tank meter was inaccurate causing the overflow which was contained in the containment dike.

column169: At 01:51 EDT on 3/14, XPO-UDV contacted ERTS to report 2 spills in the same trailer. column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: Undeclared hazmat shipment of Lithium Batteries. 5760 used computers from bush Alaska to a  re-seller via Anchorage Alaska. Lower Kuskokwim School District (LKSD) engaged with Second Life Mac (SLM)(a company from Skokie,  IL) for them to buy their used computers, and provide all services to package and transport them.  Because of the very remote location of the computers (Bethel, AK), the LKSD followed SLM's  instructions to package and deliver to the airline. SLM instructed LKSD to not mark or label any of the packages, and to cover them under black shrink  wrap, deliver to the airline, and the airline agent would take care of everything. Neither the  Airline nor Airline Agent knew anything about this shipment. 5 pallets of these items were tendered  to the Airline in Bethel, AK, and described by the shipper on our AWB as "ELECTRONICS". Shipper was  asked if there were any hazardous materials in the shipment, and shipper answered NO. Shipper  signed the Airline's AWB and initialed that there was no hazardous materials in the shipment.  5  pallets were flown from Bethel to Anchorage, AK, consignee notified 3 times without picking the  freight up, and after 3 weeks, Airline contacted the Shipper and asked what to do with the  shipment? Shipper contacted the Consignee, and they then responded that day, and arrived the next day on  sight with marking and labeling to further move these pallets on FedEx. They applied the hazmat  dimond label to the 5 pallets while on our ramp.  It had rained, and some of the boxes got wet,  soaking some contents in water, which initiated a damage freight claim process.  No action was  taken on the claim, because of two issues: one-freight charges have not been paid for, two-shipment  was abandoned for three weeks with no communication from consignee. On March 5th, Airline was  notified of a demand letter from a lawyer for a claimed damage amount.  The demand letter was  elevated to airline administration, and was the first time administration became aware of the hidden hazmat  shipment. SLM has a third party involved, Jesse Carnahan with Lynx Enterprises (Wasilla, AK). The Airline does not know how much of or who is responsible for what between Lynx and SLM. Once administration became aware of the non-declared hazmat, an investigation ensued which led to this 5800.1 report. No release or damage to the lithium batteries has been declared.
column170: Airline is reemphasizing additional questions to ask shippers with more examples of what hazmat is when asking if any hazmat is in their shipment.

column169: At 0908 ET, Eric Ramey with XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XSL. It was reported that approximately 2 gallons of UN 2586 Naxsoft 98s released from 55-gallon poly drum due to puncture from the skid. The release impacted trailer # 3233888. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site.  ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of UN2586 Naxsoft 98S product released, impacting 6’x6’ of the wooden trailer floor due to a nail puncture at the bottom of the drum. The crew utilized absorbents, simple green and water on the impacted areas and confirmed a small area on the dock apron was also impacted and treated the same way. The original punctured drum was overpacked into a 95-gallon poly drum, impacted absorbents, PPE and impacted plywood were containerized into (2) 55-gallon poly drums.  The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Our driver hooked up his hose to begin the offloading of anhydrous ammonia into a refrigeration system.  Once the hose was hooked up, the driver started pumping the liquid ammonia.  After starting the pump, the driver noticed a small leak at the hose connection.  The driver then attempted to fix the leak with out shutting the pump off and putting on his PPE.  While tightening the connection he moved the nozzle on the hose causing an aerosol of ammonia that traveled past his face which caused eye irritation due to not having goggles on.  The duration of the leak was less than one minute and the release was fixed by getting the hose nozzle tightened at the connection.
column170: This event caused additional training reminders to ensure PPE is worn while executing an activity that requires it and also cause a review of the SOP that shows the process for fixing a leak in this scenario.

column169: On 3/26/2025 at approximately 1400 hours, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 261690 at the ramp facility in Anchorage, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  This report covers 4 different shipments from the same shipper. Each package contains several bottles of perfume and cologne.  The shipments were flagged by Customs under the suspicion of potentially containing undeclared dangerous goods.  Further investigation confirmed these suspicions.  The packages were not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, as they did not display the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork. All shipments are being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.
